metadata.name: Punkasso #350
metadata.description:
Punkassos
---------
A pfp collection inspired by global events and the painting "Guernica" by Pablo Picasso.
We need to move beyond war and learn to talk to each other once again.
We need to work together locally and globally to thwart authoritarian regimes that wish to destabilize and send us back 100 years.
Never forget.
Remember the repressed from the past and help those who suffer today and will suffer in the future.
Say no to fascism, genocide, slavery, repression and suppression.
Say no to lies and propaganda.
Say no to the wealthy who wish to keep using you as a pawn.

metadata.name: Maps of Life #67
metadata.description:
Maps of Life is a generative cartographic experiment inspired by John Conway's Game of Life. The Game of Life is a zero-player game, its evolution is determined by its initial state, requiring no further input.

Maps of Life is a generative-player game, an algorithm that creates an initial random configuration and a collector that observes how the configuration evolves. Each mint produces a distinctly unique cartographic representation of an ideal town, with different color palettes, scales, and coordinates, an animation from its random birth to a stopped moment in time.

Maps of Life assumes that the built environment has a life of its own. And besides, only an automatic mind can name towns with Butterfly Names. Enjoy the view.

---
Interactivity:
Press LEFT and RIGHT arrows to speed-up or slow-down the evolution of the town.
Press "S" to save the current state to a PNG image.
If you want to change the resolution, just add "?res=XXX" to the end of the url.
---

(With these keys, you can possibly force the script to continue until its further completion. Could you get a deserted landscape?)

metadata.name: Mur #54
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: The beauty of imperfection #40
metadata.description:
Drawing shapes repeatedly, spinning and rotating. I use basic shapes like square, rectangle, and triangle to create this art. Regular shapes are perfect but it's a little bit boring, so I make them imperfect, just like "hand drawing". I also tried to make this generative art great for physical print, so that I can hang it on the wall. Here we go.

5 background colors:
Black, White, Blue, Green, and Red

Press “space” to play animation.
Press “s” to save.

Made with p5js.
Created by Costa C. | OneRocket.nft

metadata.name: Flow #257
metadata.description:
Flow is a collection of eye pleasing formula's in the form of patterns and colors.

Features include:
- Patterns
- Palettes
- Focus points
- Margins
- Sizes
- Spacings
- Color distribution patterns
- Modifiers
- Gradients
- Dots
- Overflow

Due to the large amount of calculations it may take a few seconds to generate.
The spinning indicator on the top right disappears when it is finished, this is the best moment to save.

Press [s] to save a high resolution PNG @ 9933x14043 pixels (A0 paper dimensions @ 300 DPI).

Flow By @OneDayOfCrypto, 2022

metadata.name: Strata #140
metadata.description:
A generative series inspired by the work of Vera Molnár, Strata explores the diversity that can come from one shape - the simple rectangle.

With 16 properties and ~600 palettes, I hope that each mint offers something unique and special.

Exploration is fully open and will be left open post-mint :)

metadata.name: Chord Unknown #359
metadata.description:
The feeling of experimenting with an instrument you have not learned, and then suddenly striking an actual chord.

The code creates several grids and then applies one of six unique deformation techniques with varying intensity. It's a defined process of experimentation, and even though I'm the one that wrote the rules, each output breaks through somehow as a complete surprise to me. So when I see them, I get a Chord Unknown.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.
